renavir)." Glaxo Wellcome, Research Triangle Pk, NC.[4] "Product Information. Viracept (nelfinavir)." Agouron Pharma Inc, La Jolla, CA.[5] Malaty LI, Kuper JJ "Drug interactions of HIV protease inhibitors." Drug Safety 20 (1999): 147-69[6] Piliero PJ "Interaction between ritonavir and statins." Am J Med 112 (2002): 510-1[7] Cerner Multum, Inc. "UK Summary of Product Characteristics." O 0[8] "Product Information. Norvir (ritonavir)." Abbott Pharmaceutical, Abbott Park, IL.[9] "Product Information. Lexiva (fosamprenavir)." GlaxoSmithKline, Research Triangle Park, NC.[10] Dresser GK, Spence JD, Bailey DG "Pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic consequences and clinical relevance of cytochrome P450 3A4 inhibition." Clin Pharmacokinet 38 (2000): 41-57[11] Fichtenbaum CJ, Gerber JG, Rosenkranz SL, et al. "Pharmacokinetic interactions between protease inhibitors and statins in HIV seronegative volunteers: ACTG Study A5047." AIDS 16 (2002): 569-577[12] "Product Information. Fortovase (saquinavir)" Roche Laboratories, Nutley, NJ.[13] Cheng CH, Miller C, Lowe C, Pearson VE "Rhabdomyolysis due to probable interaction between simvastatin and ritonavir." Am J Health Syst Pharm 59 (2002): 728-30[14] "Product Information. Reyataz (atazanavir)." Bristol-Myers Squibb, Princeton, NJ.[15] Hare CB, Vu MP, Grunfeld C, Lampiris HW "Simvastatin-nelfinavir interaction implicated in rhabdomyolysis and death." Clin Infect Dis 35 (2002): E111-2[16] Neuvonen PJ, Backman JT, Niemi M "Pharmacokinetic comparison of the potential over-the-counter statins simvastatin, lovastatin, fluvastatin and pravastatin." Clin Pharmacokinet 47 (2008): 463-74[17] Schmidt GA, Hoehns JD, Purcell JL, Friedman RL, Elhawi Y "Severe rhabdomyolysis and acute renal failure secondary to concomitant use of simvastatin, amiodarone, and atazanavir." J Am Board Fam Med 20 (2007): 411-6[18] Mangum EM, Graham KK "Lopinavir-Ritonavir: a new protease inhibitor." Pharmacotherapy 21 (2001): 1352-63[19] Barry M, Mulcahy F, Merry C, Gibbon